Here is the "No-BS" cheat sheet for a power user moving from Bash/Zsh to Fish.

1. Variables & Environment (The set Command)
Fish doesn't use the = sign for assignment. It uses the set function.

Action	Bash/Zsh	Fish
Local Var	foo="bar"	set foo bar
Env Var	export FOO="bar"	set -x FOO bar
Unset Var	unset FOO	set -e FOO
Path	PATH="$PATH:/new/path"	fish_add_path /new/path
Thorough Note: set -x means "export". set -e means "erase". fish_add_path is a special helper that handles idempotency—it won't double-add the path if you source your config twice.

2. Command Substitution
Bash uses backticks or $(). Fish only uses ().

Bash: count=$(ls | wc -l)

Fish: set count (ls | wc -l)

3. Logic & Conditionals
Fish does away with the brackets [[ ... ]] for most common tasks.

Bash:

Bash
if [ -f "file.txt" ]; then
    echo "exists"
fi
Fish:

Code snippet
if test -f "file.txt"
    echo "exists"
end
4. Combining Commands (The Ampersand)
This is the one that trips up everyone. Fish (historically) didn't use && or || because it preferred the words and and or. However, as of Fish 3.0+, both work.

Classic Fish: make; and make install

Modern Fish (Your Arch version): make && make install (This works now!)

5. Redirection (Standard Error)
Bash uses 2>&1. Fish uses a much more readable caret or a specific pipe.

Bash: command > file 2>&1

Fish: command &> file (The & implies both stdout and stderr)

6. The "How do I run this Bash script?" Problem
Because your interactive shell is now Fish, you can't source script.sh if that script is written in Bash.

The Hack: Don't source it. Run it: bash script.sh.

The Power User Way: Use the bass plugin (available on the AUR: yay -S fish-bass). It allows you to run Bash commands and "inject" their exported variables back into your Fish session.

Example: bass source /etc/profile

Why this is "Robust" for your Arch/Hyprland setup:
When you write scripts for Hyprland (like a toggle-mute script for Waybar), write them in Bash and use the #!/bin/bash shebang.

Keep Fish for your interactive life (the 90% of the time you are typing in Ghostty). This separates your "System Logic" (standardized Bash) from your "User Interface" (optimized Fish).

