The concern is simple: The TTY Login Risk.

On Arch, when you boot your PC and see a black screen asking for a login (a TTY), the system looks at /etc/passwd to see which shell to launch.

The Danger: If you set your shell to /usr/bin/fish and then perform a system update that breaks a Fish dependency (or you accidentally uninstall Fish), you cannot log in. The login process will crash immediately because it can't find its shell.

The "Robust" Way: Keep your user's official shell as /bin/bash (the "failsafe"), but tell your terminal emulator (Ghostty) to launch Fish instead.

Method 1: The "Ghostty" Way (Safest)
Since you use Ghostty, you can tell it to use Fish without changing your system-wide default. This ensures that if you ever drop to a TTY for emergency repairs, you’re in a stable Bash environment.

Edit ~/.config/ghostty/config:

Plaintext
command = /usr/bin/fish
Method 2: The "Tmux" Way
If you always use tmux, you can leave your shell as Bash and let tmux handle the switch.
In ~/.tmux.conf:

Code snippet
set -g default-shell /usr/bin/fish
Method 3: The "Official" Way (Use with Caution)
If you want Fish everywhere, use the chsh (change shell) command. Ensure Fish is in /etc/shells first.

Check if Fish is listed: cat /etc/shells

If not, add it: echo /usr/bin/fish | sudo tee -a /etc/shells

Change it: chsh -s /usr/bin/fish

My Recommendation
Go with Method 1. It is the most "robust" because it keeps your system's "plumbing" (Bash) separate from your "dashboard" (Fish in Ghostty). If Fish ever breaks, you can still hit Ctrl+Alt+F2 to get a working Bash TTY and fix your system.

